animal.description:
Orbit is a 2 year old male Bernese Mountain Dog rescued from a puppy mill.  He is a sweet boy learning about life outside of a mill.

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA if it’s the best fit for the dog.

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
Belle is in need of a new foster home as a member of the house has become very ill.

Belle was born in our care on April 1st 2017 to Momma Orla. She and her siblings were named after Beauty and the Beast characters. She and her 'sister' didn't get along so the family felt she would be better with a new family. She did great with her two Chihuahua siblings, and may do well with a male dog. She loves to give kisses and plays hard on toys. One of her favorite past times is to bird watch. Cats and kids are unknown at this time. She is currently in boarding and we need her out!Thank you for your interest in adopting a pet from Guardians of the Green Mile Inc. We are a group of individuals that have come together to save the lives of animals that are in danger of being euthanized. We raise funds to fully vet the animals and to provide them with a stable home until they are adopted. All of the dogs in our Rescue are in Foster homes while they are looking for their forever family. The only time we put a dog in boarding is for a Foster to go on vacation if another Foster is not able to care for them. We appreciate your taking the time to fill out the application to adopt one of our Guardians of the Green Mile pets. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
If you are reading about Oakley on PetFinder or other similar websites, please go to Bfpa.org which will provide additional information about Oakley

. All dogs on our website ARE available. OAKLEY MUST HAVE A FENCED YARD AND IDEALLY ANOTHER DOG.

FOSTER COMMENTS: Oakley is a 2 yo husky mix who weighs around 50lbs. If you are an outdoor lover, then Oakley would be your outdoor companion. He loves to go running and hiking.

Is your dog friendly or timid?

Timid but friendly. He just needs time and patience to get to know you. Meaning let him warm up to you. Don't try to train right away. Don't grab at him or hug him until he is comfortable with you.

Does your dog get along with other dogs?

Yes, He loves having a buddy. I think having another dog will help him settle in much better.

How does your dog do with cats?

He is great with cats. He tries to get ours to play with him but eventually just leaves her alone.

Has your dog been around children and if so, how did it go?

He is great with older kids. No child younger than 13. Young kids stress him.

Is your dog vocal or quiet?

He is quiet. Will occasionally bark when he lays by the front door and sees a dog outside. He will also bark/cry when left alone.

Is your foster dog housebroken? Yes

How long can your dog be left without having to go outside to do "their business"?

Up to 5 hours.

Describe your dogs activity level.low, moderate or high energy?

He has a lot of energy. However, if he has a dog buddy to play with, it helps keep his energy down. A couple of walks a day and play with my dogs and I get a lot of downtime out of him. Plays hard, sleeps hard.

Do you think your dog needs a fenced in yard or it this just a "nice to have" feature?

He absolutely needs a fenced in yard. He loves to run back and forth with my husband and loves doing zoomies with my dogs.

Are you crate training your dog and if so, how does the dog react?

He is completely crate trained. He sleeps in it at times during the day with the door open.
He sleeps in his crate at night. I've tried leaving the door open and he will stay in it until about 5am.

Are you leash walking your dog? If so, how is that going?

Yes. He is a puller. With the appropriate harness and some training, he will get better.

What are some of your fosters favorite things to do?

He loves to have his belly rubbed and be called a handsome boy. He loves his ball and will run around with it in his mouth and then throw it in the air and grab at it by himself. He has not figured out "Fetch" yet. He loves walks and just snuggling (once he is comfortable with you) absolutely loves treats. He wants to be with someone all the time. He is not a loner.

Do you think your dog could be an only dog?

He could be but I think only if there is someone home all the time. He does not like being alone. Does fine if he has a friend but when alone, he cries and whines a lot.

Do you think your foster could live in an apartment.so would be fairly quiet and OK without their own yard?

No. He needs a house and fenced in yard.

Why should someone adopt your dog, what are his/her strong points?

He is very smart, easily trainable, great companion. However, he is slow to trust. Once he does though, he is very loyal and so loving. Just a really energetic, love bug.

I really feel like a second dog is a must. It really helps with his stress and trust. We need to emphasize he needs time to adjust. It's taken 2 months for him to be a comfortable with us. He also needs to have someone who is home more than not. I'm a Stay at home mom. I do leave the house but my husband is also working from home a lot so he isn't alone ever. However when we leave, we crate him and because of my dogs. His crying out doesn't last long. He needs a lot of time to adjust and learn that he is safe. Very patient people that are very familiar with rescue dogs would be the best fit for Oakley.

Some of the information contained in this biography includes approximations based on our expertise and is not guaranteed.

Applicants must live no further than one hour from Cary NC as our dogs must be seen by a BFPA veterinarian for all medical care prior to adoptions being finalized. Our foster guardians deliver dogs to their new homes for adoption trials and we do home visits to finalize all adoptions. We therefore require applicants to live within an hours drive of Cary NC.

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING OAKLEY? If so, please fill out our dog adoption application by copying and pasting this link in a new browser window:

https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/of/f?c=WHMSYCNC

Marnie is a 4 month old Shepherd Lab mix. She has a light blonde coat and weighs in at 26 pounds.  Marnie is very sweet and can be submissive. She enjoys petting, playing, and working for treats. Marnie is learning sit for a treat and what going for walks on leash is all about. She will  do best in a home that has time to train and socialize her properly. She will need some guidance and positive reassurance when it comes to new things. If she gets afraid, she will just lay down and not move. "Come on Marnie, it's okay!" in a happy tone usually gets her to get up and move forward. She just needs to see more of the world to become more confident. Marnie is good with other dogs and we think she'd accept a cat as well too. Marnie can be a jumper, and could certainly knock over little children. We think Marnie would do best in a family home with older children.

Meet Mitten!

Mitten came to AWSJC 1/12/21 on from the BCHS after she was surrender for having issues with the child in the home.

Mitten is around 2 years old. She is timid when she first meets you, but once she is relaxed she loves attention. 
She is house broken, crate trained, and leash trained. She does have separation anxiety so she would benefit from a household where she is not left alone for long periods of time. 

Mitten is possessive over toys, food and protective of her home so with that being said she would do best in a home with no children. She would also do well in a home with no other pets. Mitten needs a family who is able to dedicate time to her. She does have a deformed jaw, but she has no trouble eating and her teeth are fine.

This girl has been given up once already, so we are hoping to find her a forever home!

Mitten is spayed, vaccinate, and microchipped!

animal.description: Hello I'm Dean! I am an amazing and loving dog in search of my forever family! I love going on walks, running around in the dog park, and playing fetch. I especially love meeting new people! I am a warm and compassionate guy who will follow you around the house to see what you're up to and to see if it's playtime or treat time. I can be a sleepy pup when I'm not busy playing and I love to take naps or just lounge around and listen to the TV. I came to Dolly's very underweight but I'm getting back to a normal and healthy weight by getting my 3 good meals a day. I am trained; I know how to sit, lay down for bed, and I haven't had any accidents in the house. I do have a very peculiar and loud cough but I just use it as my way to get your attention! I have been told I am a great listener, a loyal friend, and the sweetest dog you’ll come to know and love. It's nothing but the truth and I can't wait to meet my forever family to share all my love with! Dean is a male Chocolate Labrador possibly mixed with Spaniel born approximately 12-30-12 and weighs 70 lbs (started out at 55 lbs when he arrived). He is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, given flea/tick preventative, dewormed, tested negative for heartworm disease & started on preventative. Adoption fee is $375 to help offset the many expenses we have for vetting costs. We rely strictly on adoption fees and donations to continue to save the lives of orphaned & abandoned pets; 100% goes towards their care. If interested in adopting one of our available dogs or puppies, please complete an online adoption application at https://dollyslegacyanimalrescue.org/adopt/ You will be contacted by our adoption coordinator via email after your application has been reviewed & approved to schedule an appointment.

animal.description:
Manny Q is a statuesque, international traveler looking to settle down into his furever home. Manny Q's journey began in Qatar, where he lived on the streets until he was lucky enough to get passage to the USA and a second chance with Furkids. Unlike typical lazy American Greyhounds, Spanish Greyhounds have lots of energy and love to run around. This energetic boy loves spending time chasing a ball, but is happy to take breaks for hugs, snuggles and ear rubs...and those ears are hard to resist! Manny Q loves to show his silly side as he gallops around the yard like a majestic noodle horse. He is an affectionate boy who loves people and would be best suited as the only pet in the home. A lifetime of struggling for food on the streets has made him very protective of his dinner, which could cause problems with other dogs in the home. Manny would be best with an experienced dog owner that can continue his training and understand his quirks.
 Please consider giving this handsome globe-trotting gentleman a forever home! Manny Q weighs 52 lbs., his estimated birth date is 8/21/2018 and his adoption fee is $275. If you want more information about Manny Q, please submit a survey at https://furkids.org/dog-adoptions/application. At this time, meeting our dogs is by appointment only. After submitting a survey, an adoption counselor will contact you to give you more information about the dog you are interested in adopting and to arrange for you to meet the dog. Must be at least 21 years of age to adopt.

animal.description: Heartbreaker alert: Burrito is a sweet, senior guy who came to the shelter with some old guy issues. At 15 years old, his back legs don't work very well and he's easily startled, so he seems to be hard of hearing or possibly deaf. He also is in need of some dental work and mass removal, so he really would benefit from getting out of the shelter and into a home so he can recuperate in a calm, comforting setting In his former home, Burrito was an outdoor-only dog, so we know he'd love to find out what life inside of a home is like. Staffers say Burrito is a friendly and sweet guy. His former owner tells us he has spent time around children and reportedly did well. Burrito came to PACC with his pal, Penny, but he's sharing a kennel with a dog he just met and the two are getting along well. At 15, Burrito does not belong in the shelter, but rather inside of a loving, cozy home where he can spend the rest of his golden years showered with affection. If you've got some room in your home and heart for a dog who really needs it, make an appointment to meet Burrito today.

animal.description:
My name is Haven. Some nice man rescued me from the highway by Oasis Park in Ephrata WA. I am mostly blind but healthy otherwise. I am lucky to have great dental care and nice white teeth. I weigh a little over 10 pounds and think I am a big girl. I have to admit, I am very smart, too! When I came to my new foster home, there were many new obstacles I had to learn where they were and most important, where to find food and water. I found that right away, Yippee! The next thing I found was all the new friends I would have for company. There are 4 kitties that don't mind me poking my nose at them to smell them. They just poke me back or rub on me to show me I am welcome. My new foster parents have a dog about my size that is tolerating me, but I think she is kind of jealous that my foster mom plays with me and pets me too. We have learned to both get loves and pets equally and be happy together. But she won't share her bed with me yet. The other thing I learned very quickly is they have this portal (doggy door) to a big jungle area where we go out and go potty and I don't have to ask to go out. It took me a little while to figure out how to get back in by myself, but this makes my foster mom happy and now she doesn't worry I am going to get stuck out there and be cold and scared. Remember, I am a big girl and I learn quickly, LOL! My foster dad says I like to be a woman's dog, because I cry and howl when my foster mom goes out to her "JOB". I am so happy when she comes back and holds me and loves on me and my Rat Dog friend again. My foster mom is going to take me to see a doctor to make sure my eyes are ok and I am healthy next week. She will update more about me after that date with a doctor. Thank you for reading, Haven Oasis.

 

We are a fostered based organization. Each of our animals are kept in individual homes where their foster parents can get to know them to help them find the best possible home. If you would like to meet this pet, please fill out our Animal Inquiry form. Once we recieve it, it will be forwarded to the foster home where they will contact you and be able to answer any questions that you might have. We will also be doing adoption events at Hale's Farm and Feed in Ephrata, WA on the 2nd and 5th Saturday of each month from 10am - 2pm.
animal.name: Haven Oasis

Baloo is medium energy and would love a family to go on adventures with. He is selective with dogs, good with cats, and not good with smaller kids. He's had a heart murmur since he was a puppy but it hasn't affected him at all.

Baloo does not seem to be well socialized with dogs outside the home but does live with another dog currently. There are signs of resource guarding over food/toys but in a structured home, he should be okay with other dogs, including slow intros.

Adoption requirements are as such:


	No children under 16 
	No other dogs 
	Not a first time dog owner 
	Central Florida home 
	Large breed experience 


Baloo has to find his new forever home because his current family has a toddler and they do not feel it is the best home for him anymore. 

Please note, Baloo is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. She has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

Male Pit Bull Terrier Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Scheduled for 02/17/21

Dogs: Yes

Bruce is the cutest, squishiest and cuddliest little nugget we have ever seen! 

Bruce was found as a stray and taken into one of the shelters we partner with. He has a healed fracture on the distal end of the femur on his left hind leg, so he walks and runs with a stiff leg, but it doesn't slow him down one bit! It also doesn't seem to cause him any discomfort. 

Bruce always seems to be in a great mood, he loves everyone he meets and they love him too. He enjoys playtime like all cheery pups do, followed by some cuddles and snuggles. He is a charming young boy who deserves all the love in the world. 


*Kindly note: Prior to Bruce's sterilization surgery on February 17, we are only able to consider applicants who reside in the following Virginia counties: Clarke, Culpeper, Fauquier, Loudoun, Prince William, Rappahannock, Stafford and Warren.

animal.description:
Bentley needs his forever home as kennel life is definitely not for him!  He is an 80Lbs 4 yr old Chocolate Lab full of love, strength, motivation. He is dominate in nature.  We are not sure if he is cat friendly.  If there are children in the home, because of his size and strength, we would like them to be older.   Bentley is pretty smart and learns quickly.  He does well on a leash and is a huge fan of snow! What we have learned about Bentley since he has been with our shelter is that he absolutely hates peanut butter and he tends to have issues with men.  He loves the outdoors and would love a sunny porch to hang out on but also have nice spot inside to be with his family.  His adoption fee is $100.00.  He is neutered, UTD on shots, microchipped and heartworm negative. If you would like to meet him, please call 712-644-3003.  

**Harrison County Humane Society of Iowa reserves the right to find the right fit for our animals and not necessarily the first interested individual or family.**

Penny is a gentle soul whose is beautiful both inside and out.  She is loyal and affectionate and loves to be with her people.  Her favorite thing to do is have her belly rubbed...she will never get tired of that! You can see by her photos that she actually smiles!! Penny has impeccable house manners and is crate trained.

Penny enjoys going on walks and especially loves going to the beach. She is energetic and playful and has met a lot of doggie friends while in her foster home but will need to be the only dog in the home. Penny will need a feline free home.
 Penny is 8 years and weighs 62 pounds.

Adoption fee is $150.00
Save-A-Mutt is a registered 501c3.

Please note, we have approximately a 300 mile adoption radius. We don’t ship dogs.  Once approved you must pick them up in Snohomish County, WA *Due to the Border Closure to Canada - we are currently not accepting Canadian Adoption Applications*. Sorry.

animal.description: Cercius came with an uncertain past. A history of dog aggression and growling toward small children. She met my resident female PitBull with no fireworks. My pitbull is very laid back. While neither dog plays together they are mostly civil toward each other. Cericus knows how to sit, lay down and shake with either paw for a treat. She does throw her paws at you and will play with a tug toy.(super strong) She loves to actually sit on you as most Danes do. She is 100% house broken. She does pull quite hard on a leash and does not like the halter style gentle lead. She carries a bone around as her security blanket and will growl when you try to take it but she will give it to people without anymore than a growl. However she will go after the resident dog if she walks near while she has the bone. Today was the first day she drew blood over it but a mouthy spat happens daily. Once they spat they are fine like nothing happened. For this reason I would recommend she be an only dog and not be around small children. She sleeps on her dog bed even when she is welcomed into the human bed. She is fine for baths. She does have some old lady lumps and bumps and seems to have the start of hip arthritis. If approved I want to start her on Adequan and have her teeth cleaned. She does not counter surf or beg for people food. She is still on the thin side. She does seem to guard the house and will bark and growl at stranger's. Overall she is a super sweet gal that loves car rides, treats, and her special bone.

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

animal.description:
Name:  Brownie  5060
Age: 5 years
D.O.B.: 12/24/2015
Color: Red
Coat:  Smooth
Sex: Female/Spayed 
Size: Tweenie – 16 lbs.

Brownie past is a mystery.  She’s been passed around from home to home for the past 5 years.  This time she went from a friend of another friend who also was unable to keep her.  Luckily, Brownie landed at SCDR and we are determined to find Brownie a “forever” home.

Brownie arrived at her foster home with a cautious attitude.  She made friends quickly with her fellow foster dogs, learned the location of the dog door and took full advantage of the privilege of going in and out at her own volition.  She is not fond of going outside to potty when it is raining. (No one else in the foster home was making an effort to go out in the rain either.)
Brownie loves MEN, especially if they have a beard.  Brownie also loves going for walks and rides nicely in the car.  Her favorite thing was to be a “lap dog” as soon as she sees the man of the house sit down on the sofa.  Retired gentlemen are encouraged to apply for Brownie.  They have the best laps.  Brownie is a “big bed dog”.  On the very first night at her foster home, she let her humans know that she was not going to sleep anywhere else.  All righty then, what’s one more dog in the bed where there are several there already?

Brownie is healthy, and her vaccinations are current.  She is microchipped.  We don’t know how she feels about cats.  She is well socialized and would be fine with another small male dog.  Brownie is safe with dog-savvy children over 10 years old.  No babies, toddlers or pre-schoolers please.  Brownie is a “chiweenie”, so a home with stairs is not a serious issue.

Brownie is fully vaccinated and she’s been microchipped.  If you can give Brownie a home for the rest of her life, please contact Dena at (562) 694-6868.or email Dena@SCDR.org.  An adoption application and home check are required.

Adopt Brownie for a tax-deductible donation of $400.00.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to:
 https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to:
 https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 


PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: 
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to KayLynne.Parker@gmail.com.

Mano is working on adjusting to his new surroundings. He is a very sweet, yet fearful boy. He needs a home with a secured tall fence, no young kids under 12 & another dog in the home as he LOVES DOGS! He does not walk on a leash as of yet & would do best in a quiet/calm home. Professional Training is highly recommended to help Mano be the best boy he can be! If you have time & patience for this handsome boy the rewards will surely be worth it! 

Adoption Coordinator: KayLynne Parker
Location: Foster Home
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program



COME MEET ADOPTABLE DOGS EVERY SATURDAY AND SUNDAY from 10AM - 4PM at the Homeward Trails Adoption Center- 11116 Fairfax Station Road, Fairfax Station VA 22039! **Note that puppies are in foster homes, not at the Adoption Center.

Meet Bendy! Bendy was a surrender to us with very little information and the information that was given was all negative. We don't know his age or much about him. He is neutered and ready for adoption. Bendy does know how to sit and enjoys the company of the staff and volunteers here. He does seem to destroy some toys so he would love to play. He has lots of energy and can be perfect for an active person or couple. We received a bit more info on him since our first post about him and we were told that he has issues with being woken up. He is not a fan of being woken from his sleep, but who is? Bendy may know he's handsome, but he needs his beauty rest to look this good! Because of this, we believe that having his own area to sleep, whether that be a crate or a separate dog bed/room would be perfect. Due to the sleep issues, he will not be adopted into a home with younger children. Older kids and teens may be considered if they understand his need for sleep. 
He hasn't shown aggression here but that is due to this environment. If you are interested and have the right type of set up for this handsome fella, please call to set up an appointment at 715-284-0251.

animal.description:
STAR is a foster-based rescue. All our rescue animals stay in foster homes until adoption. We do not have a central facility. If you want to meet any of our adoptables please submit an application.

Hi! My name is Chica!

I am about 5 or 6 years old and I weigh about 44 lbs. My foster mom says I am a happy-go-lucky girl and a joy to have around. I always know how to make her smile. I have lived with kids in the past, and I probably would be okay living with dog savvy cats or dogs with slow and proper intros....but honestly I'd probably prefer to just be the only pet so I can get the undivided attention I deserve :) Some people call me a "low rider" because I kind of have a pitty face, but short beagle legs and body. I guess that also makes me "cute" because I get called that a lot as well!

To tell you a little bit about where I came from, I used to live life outside on a chain, no matter the weather. My old owners didn't take the best care of me. The amazing volunteers at STAR found me sick and weak, suffering from heatstroke. They got me surrendered and rushed me to the emergency vet. I was treated for dehydration, a severe UTI infection and they also discovered I had a heartworm infection. All of this took a toll on my body and I'm greatful they rescued me just in time!

Now that I'm feeling SO much better and I'm back to my normal self, I am currently in the process of going through heartworm treatment, though I am available to be adopted at anytime. In the the meantime, for about another month, my activities will need to be kept to a minimum - so all those fun runs and adventures and hikes will have to wait, but that's perfect because it's cold outside right now anyway ;)

One of my favorite "go-to" snacks is pill pockets, even though I really don't need to take medications anymore. I also really love to chew on bones and bully sticks, and generally I don't chew on things that aren't mine and I don't tend to destroy my stuffed toys. I walk pretty well on a leash, but I don't get too much practice since currently I have a fenced in yard.

If you are interested in meeting me and taking care and loving me, please fill out an application or you can email my foster mom at heather@savingtailsanimalrescue.org My adoption fee is $265 and includes all my vetting up to date, some food and treats, toy, leash and collar.

Thank you for considering a special girl like me!

All STAR animals come vetted, Up to Date (UTD) on age appropriate shots and testing, spay and neutered (if of age,) and microchipped.

AGE DISCLAIMER:
Unfortunately, most of the orphaned animals that come into our rescue looking for homes don't bring birth certificates. Sometimes we know our pets' ages. Sometimes we don't. So we make our best guess based on the condition of their teeth and the veterinarians best guess.
BREED DISCLAIMER:
Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality,
not
by breed label .
Microchips:
For the safety of our dogs and peace of mind of our fosters and adopters, STAR microchips all dogs prior to adoption with Petlink Microchips. Please understand that all dogs MUST still wear a collar with ID tags (which include your current information) AT ALL TIMES. Please remember, our foster dogs are extremely important to us-- we will always take any of our dogs back, if for any reason you can't keep your adopted dog. Never surrender him/her to a shelter!
animal.name: Chica

animal.description:
Currently taking applications. Our puppies are not placed on a first come/first served basis. We strive to find the best home for each of our animals. If you are interested in meeting and adopting, please complete an application on our website (uaaf.org).

Oliver is one of a litter of five puppies born November 14, 2020. His mom was surrendered while she was still pregnant. The puppies have had a really good start to life. They have stayed with their mother from birth to the present day. In their foster home, they have been exposed to animals, people and lots of different sights and smells.  They are all confident and adventurous, just like puppies should be!

Oliver was the runt of the litter, but you’d never know it to look at him now. He is as active, playful and pudgy as his brothers and sisters. Oliver is also very interested in cuddling with his humans. He is a very sweet boy.

Before you adopt a puppy, remember that they like to chew, chew, chew when they are bored, so they will need plenty of exercise and toys to chew on.  Oliver and his brother, Cyrus, are available for adoption now. Their sisters, Brandi and Scarlett will be available in a week or two after they are spayed.

Oliver has been neutered and microchipped.  At 9 weeks, he has only received his first canine combination booster shot. His adoptive parents will need to get his second and third boosters, as well as a rabies vaccination and heartworm test when he is six months old.

We are committed to doing our part to control the spread of the COVID-19 virus. Until life goes back to normal, we will not be doing adoption events at PetSmart. Instead, we will be doing individual meetings by appointment and practicing social distancing at each meeting.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete our online adoption application at www.uaaf.org. For more information, or to schedule an appointment, call/text Kirsty at (435) 671-0985, or email kirsty.ju@gmail.com

Skittles is a 2-year-old hound mix that is just as sweet as sugar! Skittles has met our veterinarian and our behaviorist plus has hung out with a bunch of our staff members too. He did outstanding with our entire team! So much that our behaviorist left a great review in his file. This is part of her report: 

"Skittles seemed to be a super-smart dog who learns commands very quickly. He knew "Sit" and by the time we were done with everything he learned "Touch" and was catching onto Shake and Down. If startled he will lower himself or try to get away. He would lower and flinch if I touched his butt but quickly loosened and raised body once he realized I was just petting him. Seems very dog friendly but can be rude when first introduced. As long as the adopters continue working on his manners with both people and dogs I think he will thrive in almost any home (as long as there are no cats). I truly can't say enough how smart and willing to please this sweet boy is."

Skittles is house-broken and crate trained. He is good on leash too. 
Skittles is already neutered, vaccinate, heartworm tested negative and up to date on all flea/tick and heartworm medication. To meet Skittles, please check out our online survey at http://www.secondchancenorman.com/index.php?survey

animal.description:
The Three Musketeers (Athos, Porthos, and Aramis) are lab mixed puppies rescued from the city of San Bernardino, CA. While a volunteer was washing his car, a man stopped by the car wash. The man put the three puppies who seemed to be a month old in a plastic pen outside of his vehicle and a guy working in the wash place started washing the back seat of the man's car. Our volunteer asked the owner of the puppies why he had left the puppies in a small pen. He said that his female dog gave birth to them a month ago and he was on his way to relinquish them to the nearest shelter as he could not take care of them. While on his way, the puppies urinated the back seat of his car and left it dirty. The man got mad and decided to immediately stop by a car wash to save his newly purchased car. 

The owner of the three puppies stressed on the fact that he does not want to keep them and what made the matter worse from his point of view is that they urinated his car. Our volunteers mentioned to the man that shelters are open by appointment only. Therefore, they will not allow him to walk-in. The man was upset as he wanted to get rid of the puppies as soon as possible. Thus, our volunteer asked the rescue to take position of the puppies who seemed so malnurished with their rib cages showing under their skin. From day #1 and after the first wellness exam, the puppies followed a deworming protocol along with a nutrition protocol. As they continued to grow and gain weight, the puppies received their shots of vaccines and waited in the rescue enough to the receive complete boosters of their vaccines. At a foster home, the puppies were socialized around kids and other dogs. Finally, the puppies were operated for Neuter and received their rabies shot. (all the basic necessary veterinarian work needed for a healthy puppy was done on the expenses of the rescue). All vaccines are valid for 1 year.

All puppies are sweet, energetic, and super outgoing. They can lay with you on a couch watching TV or go with you on a long walk. 

Since they are still puppies, they are easy to train and adapt to your lifestyle. 

If you think that the description of the puppies match your criteria in a companion, please consider giving them a loving home. 

The adoption process consists of three steps: 

1- Fill and submit an adoption application through the following link

www.petember.com/adoption-application 

2- If approved, a one-to-one meet and greet will be scheduled between the adopter, his family and the puppy to be adopted. You can bring your current dog too. (Make sure to wear a mask and abide by social distancing guidelines).

3- Finalizing adoption paperwork for the puppy, paying adoption fee, and take the puppy home same day. 

The puppies will be adopted very soon. We receive hundreds of applications for each dog. Submitting your application earlier will increase your chances of being accepted. 

Applications will be reviewed immediately.

animal.description:
STAR is a foster-based rescue. All our rescue animals stay in foster homes until adoption. We do not have a central facility. If you want to meet any of our adoptables please submit an application.

Hi! My name is Marshmallow! My foster mom calls me Momma Marshmallow because I am a momma to 4 sweet babies. They have all been adopted into loving homes, and now it is my turn to find my forever family!! I am a petite little thing, weighing in about 40-42lbs. I am a little shy at first to new people, but I love treats and snacks and once I warm up to you, I will always be at your side. I LOVE to be pet and cuddled and held. I get along with other animals including dog savvy cats. I love to be home and chill with my family, but I also ride really well in the car if we go someplace new. I don't pull to hard on a leash, and I listen to my foster mom. I like to stay close and I'm a very happy girl that's easy to please. If you are interested in meeting a girl like me, please fill out an application as that is the first step. www.savingtailsanimalrescue.org

I am up to date on my vaccinations, spayed, and microchipped. I am current on flea/tick/heart worm medication and I am heartworm negative. I would come with a leash, collar, some toys, treats and food. Thank you for considering a sweet girl like me!

All STAR animals come vetted, Up to Date (UTD) on age appropriate shots and testing, spay and neutered (if of age,) and microchipped.

AGE DISCLAIMER:
Unfortunately, most of the orphaned animals that come into our rescue looking for homes don't bring birth certificates. Sometimes we know our pets' ages. Sometimes we don't. So we make our best guess based on the condition of their teeth and the veterinarians best guess.
BREED DISCLAIMER:
Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality,
not
by breed label .
Microchips:
For the safety of our dogs and peace of mind of our fosters and adopters, STAR microchips all dogs prior to adoption with Petlink Microchips. Please understand that all dogs MUST still wear a collar with ID tags (which include your current information) AT ALL TIMES. Please remember, our foster dogs are extremely important to us-- we will always take any of our dogs back, if for any reason you can't keep your adopted dog. Never surrender him/her to a shelter!

animal.description:
Happy Birthday Gary Groot!My siblings and I decided to sponsor this life saving transport to honor our father's 81st birthday. Our father, Gary Groot, is the main reason we are all animal lovers. We grew up watching and learning how to properly pamper our puppies and he instilled in us the importance of adoption; how it saves lives. My father just lost his beloved Precious who he loved with all his heart and took her everywhere, even bought a travel trailer so she could join him on mission projects for the church. Precious was by his side for the last 15 years and will now wait for him at the Rainbow Bridge. Suzanne, Karen & Tom

Ophelia and her 5 siblings were born around January 7, 2020, and may top out in the 60-65 pound range. Please understand we are truly guessing on the breed for this family. Some of the siblings have a more Retriever look while others we feel have more of a Collie appearance to them. They are wonderful with the other dogs and adore us, humans. It is likely they did not have much human interaction while growing up and so we anticipate you will have some basic training to do. They are sweet-natured, intelligent, teens, so training should go smoothly. This is all we know so far and we will be learning as we go and so will you.
The Adoption Fee for this dog is $500.00
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

In memory of Mike and Laura Bysiek.Sisters Jean (Mike) Gonska and Lorraine (Larry) Diggs, wanted to leave a lasting legacy in memory of their loving parents by establishing the Mike & Laura Bysiek Memorial Fund at the Cattaraugus Region Community Foundation to support a number of nonprofit organizations in the community each year.
As long-time active volunteers at Joyful Rescues and seeing the amazing, awe-inspiring, life-saving, tireless work that is done every day there, it was a wonderful option to be able to sponsor a life-saving pet transport annually in their honor.
Herbie was born around January 7, 2019, and weighs about 23 pounds. Herbie was surrendered to a high kill shelter in the south along with 11 other dogs from the same home. For breeds, we feel they are mostly Chia/Terrier mixes but there are likely a dozen more breeds mixed in. They get along wonderfully with the other dogs and have sweet, happy, dispositions. You will likely have some housetraining to do but it shouldn't take long as they seem eager to please and are smart little cookies. This is all we know so far and we will be learning as we go and so will you! Update from foster mom: Herbie is a doll!!! He is not noisy which we love and he is the HAPPIEST little guy! When he met his foster dad for the first time he about knocked himself over from his wagging tail. He is busy and fun when it is time and he is a true cuddler whenever you sit down. He adores his humans and although we've not had him around children I can't imagine a problem. What a wonderful little guy - SO glad we could save him.
The Adoption Fee for this dog is $500.00

animal.description:
In memory of Mike and Laura Bysiek.Sisters Jean (Mike) Gonska and Lorraine (Larry) Diggs, wanted to leave a lasting legacy in memory of their loving parents by establishing the Mike & Laura Bysiek Memorial Fund at the Cattaraugus Region Community Foundation to support a number of nonprofit organizations in the community each year.
As long-time active volunteers at Joyful Rescues and seeing the amazing, awe-inspiring, life-saving, tireless work that is done every day there, it was a wonderful option to be able to sponsor a life-saving pet transport annually in their honor.
Lola was born around January 7, 2019, and weighs about 40 pounds. Lola does well with the other dogs and rode well in the car on the long trip North. Lola has been an absolute pleasure to care for and keeps her living space very tidy! She is unassuming and eager to please. She craves our attention and would like to snuggle all day. This is all we know so far and we will be learning as we go and so will you! She came to us as a Border mix, but one of us feels strongly she is, or is very close to being, a pure Aussie.
UPDATE: Lola does not have a tail! We don't know if she was born this way or someone decided to dock the tail. We are hoping she was born this way as tail docking is a barbaric practice and should be outlawed! We have found her to be a counter surfer and may submissive pee. This behavior is easy to curb as the dog becomes more self confident and if her humans react appropriately. There is a lot of information on line about this subject. One more thing we've discovered is she is mouthy with those she loves. We are teaching her 'no bite!' but she has a habit of putting her mouth on your hand, arm and even your elbow! She doesn't bite down, but her teeth are still on human skin which is inappropriate. So, we've told you as much bad as we've found and on the flip side she is not a big barker (which we love), she's simply gorgeous and soft, and extremely sweet and loving. Truly, if she'd have come in when I had a dog loss she might well be a keeper! A bit of a diamond in the rough, but I'm convinced a diamond will one day shine.
The Adoption Fee for this dog is $500.00

animal.description: Walter is a FIGHTER. While he has only lived a few years, he experienced many hardships. TXHH rescued him back in August from the streets and he was very malnourished and had severe skin issues. Now he is THRIVING. He's been with TXHH fosters to help gain his strength back and we know now that he is a very gentle dog, who loves getting scratches and cuddles. Some days he is very active, but others he just enjoys relaxing and sleeps the day away. He also can be very talkative and loves attention! He's not so much into toys, but he'll lay down to enjoy a delicious, yummy bone. Because he is a very gentle soul, he needs a calm and relaxing home. He loves his walks but barking dogs and loud noises can frighten him. Are you, or do you know, someone that could make his life complete? This survivor deserves the world. He's currently an office dog at TXHH Leander Adoption Center so drop by, ask a staff member to see him and pay this sweetie a visit!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Danish is a beautiful lady who will melt your heart with her bushy tail wags and constant nuzzling for pets. Although a little skittish on first meeting new people and dogs, once she's established trust she is all affection.

Danish is still adjusting to life inside and is working on perfecting her potty training so will require some patience and additional training as she learns. She is crate trained and is incredibly well behaved in her crate for down time and through the night. Danish should ideally go to a home where she does not need to be crated for more than a few hours a day - she has energy to burn and loves to be out and about with people.

Danish tested incredibly well with the cat in Texas, but due to her alleged history of killing livestock, might proceed with a bit of caution. She does appear to be a bit reactive to other dogs on leashes who are pulling towards her or barking at all and will require slow and patient introductions to other dogs. As you can see from the video, she has already established trust with our resident dog and is getting more and more comfortable and playful with him by the day. She definitely likes to be dominant so would do well with lower energy dogs who are willing to be submissive. When she's wound up, she really loves to play! With the right match, I think Danish could thrive in a home with another dog.

This girl is a looker with a great personality who just needs someone with the patience and experience to help her ease into her new comfortable indoor lifestyle.

Danish has had at least one litter of puppies in her past but is now spayed. She will need heartworm treatment upon adoption which will require lots of rest but is very manageable.

Danish was surrendered to a high kill shelter in Texas for allegedly killing livestock.If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description:
STAR is a foster-based rescue. All our rescue animals stay in foster homes until adoption. We do not have a central facility. If you want to meet any of our adoptables please submit an application.

Hi! My name is Blueberry! I'm a happy and playful puppy! I was part of an unwanted litter and found myself at animal control but a nice foster lady got me out of doggie jail because a shelter is no place for a pup like me! I am now on the hunt for my forever family. I love everyone I meet and I love playing with toys and chewing on bones. If you are interested in meeting me, please fill out an application. Thank you! My adoption fee is $350 ($50 is refundable when I am neutered)I come up to date on my vaccinations, microchipped, on flea/tick/worm prevention medication and I also will come with some food, treats, toys, leash and collar. If you are interested in meeting me, please fill out an application ASAP. www.savingtailsanimalrescue.org

All STAR animals come vetted, Up to Date (UTD) on age appropriate shots and testing, spay and neutered (if of age,) and microchipped.

AGE DISCLAIMER:
Unfortunately, most of the orphaned animals that come into our rescue looking for homes don't bring birth certificates. Sometimes we know our pets' ages. Sometimes we don't. So we make our best guess based on the condition of their teeth and the veterinarians best guess.
BREED DISCLAIMER:
Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality,
not
by breed label .
Microchips:
For the safety of our dogs and peace of mind of our fosters and adopters, STAR microchips all dogs prior to adoption with Petlink Microchips. Please understand that all dogs MUST still wear a collar with ID tags (which include your current information) AT ALL TIMES. Please remember, our foster dogs are extremely important to us-- we will always take any of our dogs back, if for any reason you can't keep your adopted dog. Never surrender him/her to a shelter!
animal.name: Blueberry

****DO NOT SEND AN INQUIRY VIA PETFINDER--YOU MUST GO TO WWW.OREGONDOGRESCUE.ORG AND COMPLETE AN APPLICATION--WE WILL NOT SEE INQUIRIES SENT VIA THIS POSTING!!****

Please do not call to check on your application: we will contact you within 24 hours. Make sure to answer your phone & check your email. If we can not reach you and schedule a meeting within 24 hours we will move on to the next applicant. 

We can not respond to every application at this time.

Pets may be viewed by appointment only for applicants who are approved to adopt after filling out an application at http://www.oregondogrescue.org/adoptionapplication

Approved Applicants will be contacted and appointments scheduled within 24 hours. All family members must be present (including other dogs). Please be ready to adopt before sending an application. We do not do holds and once dogs are posted they are ready to go home.

We do not keep applications on file.

Once you have submitted an application:
*Answer your phone   *Check your e-mail  *Check our website: dogs come down as soon as they are no longer available!

No cats, please!

My Adoption fee is $425

animal.description:
Meet Dunn! He is approx. 10 months old and 12 lbs. Dunn was rescued from a hoarding situation with many other dogs. He is still learning how to adjust to his new surroundings and having people around him all the time! Despite arriving with a broken leg, he has made huge strides in just a few weeks with his foster. Dunn bonds with his main caregiver quicker than other members in the house. He does not like when the children in the home run through or make loud noises so for this reason we're requiring an adult-only home. He's currently fostered with dogs of all sizes and after proper introductions, he does very well with them. Dunn loves to play with the younger dogs in the house. He would be really happy in a home that has another playmate for him! With a dedicating adopter and time to decompress, Dunn is an amazing and loving little guy that deserves the best after such a rough start in life! 

Due to his current training plan, applicants without a yard are currently not being considered for Dunn. 

This animal is currently being foster in New Jersey and will require potential adopters to go there for a meet and greet or adoption.

This animal's adoption fee is $300

animal.description:
Jackie and Kelso have a heartbreaking story, but these precious pups are full of hope! Jackie (left) and Kelso (right) arrived at The Animal Protection League after spending a month all alone when their owner passed away. They were heartbroken and afraid to be in a shelter after losing both their family and their home. With the help of our dedicated staff and volunteers, Jackie and Kelso have come out of their shells and their pleasant personalities truly shine. Jackie (female) is 4 years old and Kelso (male) is 5. They're active, playful, and tons of fun! They previously lived with both cats and dogs, so we expect them to do well in a pet friendly home. Jackie and Kelso have not spent much time with children, but they're friendly and social and would likely enjoy the company of respectful kiddos. We'd love to keep this dynamic duo together. Do you have room in your heart and home for Jackie and Kelso? 

If you're interested in adopting Jackie and Kelso, please complete an application at: inapl.org/adoption-application. Applications are not necessarily on a first come, first served basis. Our team will make adoption decisions based on the best fit for the dynamic duo. We expect Jackie and Kelo to be a popular pups, so any questions can be directed at adopt@inapl.org vs. calling the shelter. Their combined adoption fee is $250 and includes spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip, dewormer, 30 days of pet health insurance, and a free wellness exam.

Jackie & Kelso
Jack Russell/Pug mixes
Jackie DOB: 1/16/2017
Kelso DOB: 1/16/2016
Heartworm Negative

animal.description:
Jasper is absolutely a lap dog! He slept well in the crate with a nice new dog bed the first couple of nights in his foster home. Now he sleeps in his foster mom's bed. So far he's been good with her daughter. He has another dog bed close to her desk in her office, so that he can sit near her during the day. He will scratch at her legs when he wants to sit in her lap. She has built him a makeshift steps off her one-step back porch to help him get to the ground. He does have a few bursts of energy where he likes to play with his small soft toys! He is a little hard of hearing, and his vision isn't what it used to be! He is a 13-year-old Shih Tzu. He currently weighs 20 pounds, but he is on a diet to get some weight off of him. He is doing better on going potty outside, but his new family will need to continue working with him!!
Adoption application at https://www.shelteranimalsrescue.org/adoption.shtmlVisit the SARG, Inc. website for more information about our policies, events, and to submit an online application for one of our animals: https://www.shelteranimalsrescue.org.

 She was severely neglected as a pup and carries those memories with her to this day. 
She needs a very patient person  to work with her to win her over..
She will be a foster to adopt ONLY.
 She needs another playful dog in the home to help her make this cross over.
 She REQUIRES A FENCED YARD.

Once she trusts you she starts to shine brighter than the sun, she pours her love on you each and every minute of every day, she showers you with kisses, she wants to be with you always, she loves to go for adventurous walks, if you are not keeping up she will give you her goofy look as if to say hurry up.. she loves to romp in the backyard playing fetch, she absolutely loves all kinds of squeaky toys..

 She knows many commands and is a GREAT dog once she trusts you, this is a companion dog that loves with her whole heart.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THIS DESCRIPTION THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING FURTHER ABOUT THIS DOG.  IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN APPLYING TO ADOPT, PLEASE DO NOT REPLY VIA PETFINDER, INSTEAD GO TO  www.arizonapoodlerescue.org TO THE “Adopt Me” SECTION TO FIND OUR ONLINE APPLICATION.  WE WILL NOT ADOPT OUR DOGS OUT OF STATE.   PLEASE RESPECT OUR PROCESS AND OUR TIME AS WE ARE ALL VOLUNTEERS.  WE WILL BE GLAD TO ANSWER QUESTIONS ABOUT THIS DOG ONCE WE HAVE AN APPLICATION IN HAND.  PLEASE NO PHONE CALLS! 

Ben is a 7.5 lb., 11 year old 3 legged active  toy poodle whose owner became ill and could no longer care for him.  Ben never acts his age, is very sweet, loving and cuddly.  He barks when he wants out, wants attention, treats or dinner.  Ben would not be good in an apartment or condo.  He might need a little reminding that outside is where he needs to potty.   Ben gets along with other dogs.

There is an application and possible home visit or reference check prior to adoption.   Applications can be found on our website www.arizonapoodlerescue.org.   Click on the "Adopt Me" tab.    Ben is being fostered in Chandler.  His adoption fee is $150.

Arizona Poodle Rescue is an all volunteer non-profit organization.  We do not have a shelter.  Our dogs are currently being fostered in private homes generally located in the Phoenix and Tucson area.

animal.description: Hi my name is Honey . I'm about a year old (in the inside I'm only a few months old though). When you look into my big soulful eyes you'll see the most loyal and loving dog. I will need some time to adjust to my new home but once I do I will be at your side forever. I still get a little nervous when I can't see my pack but I'm working on it. I am highly treat motivated and have learned "sit", "paw", making progress on "down", "stay" and "come". My fosters say I'm very smart and a fast learner. I LOVE other dogs, and would love to have a doggy friend in my new home. I would love a friend big enough for me to wrestle (I love wrestling) but I respect other dogs' boundaries if they don't want to play. Other than playing with dogs I love chewing on consumable toys and stuffed animals. I walk well on a leash and have learned to love car rides. I am working on potty training and do best when I have a quiet, private (other dogs are ok) space outside. So my fosters think a fenced in yard would be the best for me. I like hanging out in my crate but sleep under/in my fosters' bed right now. I love to end the day with snuggles on the couch. I have a lot of love to give and I'm excited to find a family I can love with all my heart forever.

animal.description: Hi! I’m Beans, formerly known as Diamond but not completely attached to any name so open to suggestions:) I have a bit of a long story. A nice lady rescued me from an abusive situation and convinced my former owner to give me up so I could have a chance for a happy life. She REALLY REALLY wanted to keep me but there were some personality conflicts with her fur kids so I find myself here looking for my forever home. I am an 8 year old pitbull/American bulldog mix and I have SO much love to give. I know lots of tricks - sit, stay, down, and high five. I am house broken and crate trained and can hold it for up to 9 hours (but prefer to go frolic outside a little more often than that). I am a pretty low maintenance/low energy dog - I love just laying around and sleeping all day and I have the cutest little snore. I particularly like lounging on couches but am really good at getting off the furniture when I am told. I also come with my very own awesome dog bed which I LOVE. I like giving kisses but don’t require a ton of attention and am fine entertaining myself if you have work to do or can’t play with me. I love people so so so much!!! Now that we got some of the good stuff out of the way, here’s the rest. I would probably do best in a home where I would be an only pet. I have some problems with guarding food and toys and would really prefer not to share these with any other animals. I do well playing with dogs outside but I do not want to live with them or have them around my stuff. That being said, I’m ok if my human touches me while I am eating or playing. They don’t think I have lived with kids but play well with the older neighbors when they are outside (ages 9 and 12). I have not been around or tested with younger children. I am also not a huge fan of cats. I used to pull on the leash but this lady bought me a front clip harness so now am much better but she would say I am a work in progress when it comes to taking walks - I start off fast but tire out pretty quickly. I am allowed to roam around the whole upstairs when my current host leaves for work and have not gotten into or chewed up ANYTHING. I am a really good girl when it comes to that. As I said, I generally just sleep all day. I am a bit overweight and will need to lose a few pounds. They thought I might have arthritis but the Vet said I am just fat and once the extra weight comes off, I’ll move even better. Last thing, I am prone to chronic ear infections. My last owner didn’t take very good care of me and did not address this problem so I have a lot of scarring in my ear canals which is what is leading to the infections. The good news is they are looking really good now thanks to my medicine. I am up to date on all my vaccines as of November. Anyone out there looking for someone like me? I am low energy and promise to love you with all my heart if you give me a chance.
animal.name: Beans

animal.description:
Adoptable Georgia is a sweet approximately 6 year old pittie. She loves people but seems to prefer adults, teenagers stress her out a bit, and would do best in an all adult home. Georgia has seen a veterinary behaviorist for anxiety. Noises (noises occurring outside when she is inside - ie. car or truck noises, construction work noise, fireworks, storms) and boundaries (people outside while she is inside) are issues for Georgia. The veterinarian has prescribed medication to Georgia to help with her anxiety. She happily takes her medication. She comes running when she hears a pill bottle being opened because she knows she is about to get a tasty treat. The medication helps her to be a happier, calmer dog. Georgia is not crate trained. She would likely hurt herself trying to get out of a crate. She has free range in her current home and has never been destructive. She loves attention and being with people. She will sit on your feet or on your lap if able. She likes chin scratches, belly rubs, butt scratches, and snuggling on the couch. She enjoys playing with sturdy stuffed toys (otherwise they don't last long), tug, running after a ball, and rolling in the grass or on a carpet. She also loves a sunny spot, either inside or outside. Georgia loves fruits and vegetables. Some of her favorites are fresh red bell pepper and cucumber as well as frozen blackberries. Georgia travels well in a car. She does not seem to like colder weather but does like a sweater on a chilly day.

Georgia would do best with a fenced yard to run around in. She has weekly zoomies that are usually short bursts. While she does enjoy going on walks, she is very reactive to other dogs on leash, whether she sees them or just hears them, which can make walking her very challenging. Georgia has had limited experience with other dogs off leash. She would do best as an only dog in the home, who does not have interactions with other dogs.

Georgia is a smart girl who is highly treat motivated. She has solved all the dog puzzles she has been given, purchased or homemade. She knows sit, down, wait, shake, high five, watch me, touch (nose to palm), fist bump (nose to fist), bed (go to), hungry (runs to where her food is kept), and go to place (working on duration). She sits nicely until being told "okay" before eating. She has also learned a positive interrupter signal which helps to distract or redirect her from noises she finds scary. Georgia's reaction when a visitor comes to the door is challenging and a work in progress.
animal.name: Georgia

animal.description:
HSMC Adoption applications must be done at www.hsmcohio.org Please do NOT click on the "Adopt Me" button on this bio. It is only a pet inquiry. If you have additional questions about this dog, please call the shelter at 614-879-8368 or contact us through our website!

Kodiak is a ~3-year-old, 56 lb shepherd who arrived at the shelter on 1/14/21 as a stray.  Kodiak loves to play with toys, especially tennis balls and anything that squeaks and even knows how to fetch! He is a very happy outgoing guy once he gets comfortable with where he's at and the people around him.
With other dogs he can be overly playful and a little rude, so he may become too overwhelming for other playmates. With cats we are not sure how he'd respond as he is super active and ready to play, and chase, so a home without cats would probably be best for him. Since he is such a sweet young boy with energy to spend, a home without smaller children would probably be best. Kodiak seems so be crate trained and understand some basic commands. Kodiak is a great dog ready for his forever home!

Our adoption fees vary, Shelter Dogs are $150, Prison Dogs are $200, Puppies are $250, and Popular Pure-Breeds are $400. The price includes: a Home Again Microchip, set of shots, de-worming, heartworm testing (if old enough), spay or neuter, and a 1 year rabies shot (if old enough). All dogs adopted must leave with a county license at an additional cost of $17, this fee is cash only. Adoption fees can be done using credit card or cash.  If you are interested in this dog, please call the shelter at 614-879-8368 or fill out an online application at www.hsmcohio.org
animal.name: Kodiak - Prison Training

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.DOG LOCATION: Ajax, ON. Meet Benson. He is a 3 1/2 year old poodle mix who is just as cute as can be! Who wouldn't love that face?!

Benson weighs approximately 67 lbs and, well, he could stand to lose some weight. About 15-17lbs! It's a strict diet for this boy. Thankfully he is taking it well and doesn't beg for food, though food left out at his level is fair game.

This extra weight is really not good for Benson because he has some issues with his hips and it would be better for him if he was fit and trim. This will be the goal for his new family.

Benson has a tendency to want to guard the things he loves so he's learning to trade and so far he thinks this is a good game. We'll want his training to continue so he knows it's fun to share but because of this issue we do not recommend him in a home where there are children under the age of 16.

As a young dog Benson had a few meetings with dogs that didn't go well so Benson is unsure of other dogs. He'll need a home of his own, without other dogs or cats.

Please note Benson is not suited to apartment or townhouse living and he sheds so is not suitable for families who have allergies.

If you are interested in Benson, Please email us to start the conversation.

animal.description:
Hi there!  My name is MILO.  What’s yours?  Nice to meet ya!  

WATCH MY VIDEO:  https://youtu.be/C6OmmW1qWzY

https://youtu.be/7j6NvJyryLo

A nice person came along and took me in and, now, I am ready to hit the road to your house!  Uh, make that “our” house, OK?  I definitely need a house with a fenced-in yard cuz I need room to run and romp and be safe!  The rescue requires (1) a fenced-in yard and (2) a vet reference from a vet that you have used for a current or previous dog to be sure that all vetting was done and (3) a comparable-sized doggie sibling)  

I am a Retriever/Staffy mix.  I am 10 MONTHS old and I weigh 55-60 pounds. I have been neutered and am up to date on vaccines so I'm ready to go to my new home with YOU!!  Those funny-looking 2-legged creatures said I’m also microchipped – whatever THAT is.  At any rate, I am fully vetted.  Is that anything close to petted?  I love to be petted!  They say I'm precious.  Hmmm, Is my name Milo or Precious?

Wanna hear some more good stuff about me?  OK, here goes.  I like ALL people and ALL dogs.  I need to have a DOGGIE SIBLING about my size so we can run and romp together and burn up LOTS and LOTS of energy!   I know basic commands.  I respond very well to consistent, positive reinforcement training and I'm a good learner!  Smart, huh?

I am attentive, affectionate, silly, playful and loyal.  I LOVE cuddles, car rides, holding hands and tummy rubs.  I am a beta doggie.  I back down when prompted by aggressive dogs. I'm an amazing companion!

I have lots to learn.  Will you teach me all the things a pup needs to know to be safe and happy? I LOVE to give kisses so get ready!  

If you have children, then need to be older children - 12 and up because I like to play hard and run fast!  It's fun!

I like to take naps when I'm tired from playing.  I need  love, exercise and couch-sitting when we get tired!  Let's be a team, OK?

If you would like to take me home (and you know you do), please email rescuedogsgalore@gmail.com  and they can get me on my way to a new and loving home!  My adoption fee is $150 and includes my vetting, neutering, and a microchip.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Bear! I was rescued by another dog rescue organization in Florida before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I am very sweet and loving with people, but I am usually not a fan of other dogs and would prefer to be the only dog in the home. I love to go for nice long-leashed walks and would be just ecstatic to finally find myself a home where I could have my very own yard to run around and play in. I do have a lot of energy for my age and would not make a very good apartment dog. I would be happiest living in an adult-only home and do have a decent prey drive and should be kept away from cats and other small animals. I am house-broken and crate trained already! I can be protective of my food, treats, and toys. I am normally a very mellow pup but can be a little aggressive at times if provoked. I would really benefit from an experienced dog owner who can help me work through the fearfulness that prompts my negative behaviors and learn to cope with it appropriately.

animal.description:
Bonjour! I am Poppie, a 5-year-old Pit Bull who loooooves people and hates kennels. I like to be a free girl, what can I say? The kind folks here at MaxFund have been working with me on basic commands. So far, I have mastered how to sit, and I am very polite on walks! 

While I am a friendly little girl, I can be a little unsure of some dogs. The best way to go about making new friends, would be with slow introductions once I get used to being your forever companion. I am potty trained, but please be patient with me while I adjust to a new home. If you think we could be best friends forever, call MaxFund (303-595-4917) to set up an appointment to come play with me!

MaxFund is a physical shelter located at 1005 Galapago St in Denver, Colorado.
If you are interested in learning more about a dog, please call 303-595-4917 to make an appointment to meet a dog

This PetFinder account is managed by volunteers, and the most up-to-date information is at the shelter.
How our adoption process works:
1. You MUST come into the shelter to meet a dog you are interested in (and meet a few others, while you’re at it!)
               
                Our hours are 10-5 Mon, Wed, Thu Fri / 11-5 Saturday / 12-5 Sunday
                We suggest you call ahead to be sure the dog(s) do not have pending applications
2. You will fill out your adoption application, including references, after finding a dog you’d like to adopt
3. The application review and reference checks will take up to 3-5 business days; you will not be able to bring a dog home same-day
                We only take 2 applications per dog, before they are unavailable. This is why we suggest you call ahead to check the status of the pup!
 
We do not adopt out-of-state.
Thank you for choosing to rescue!

THIS PET IS NOT AVAILABLE THROUGH BROTHER WOLF ANIMAL RESCUE. 
PLEASE CONTACT THE OWNER FOR MORE INFORMATION OR TO MAKE AN APPLICATION FOR ADOPTION. 

The owner's email is: jbarrettmynes@gmail.com

My son and I tried to adopt Mister. He is a bird dog about 40 lbs. He is a sweet old fellow who has never gotten to live inside. He has some arthritis in his front shoulder and the cold concrete floor up in the mountains makes mornings rough for him. I tried to take him in but it turns out he cannot be in a home with a cat, though he has gotten along well with my other dogs. He is going to have to return to the shelter as I have 2 cats in danger and cannot keep them separated long term. Mister is from Appalachian Animal Rescue Center in Franklin, NC. We have a very limited number of fosters here in my area and most of them have cats. Mister is very social with other dogs. He did well with mine and pleasant with other dogs passed when out walking. I will send the video and pictures. Any help would be greatly appreciated for this very kindly older gentleman.

animal.description:
Meet "Rusty". This 2 1/2 yr old purebred bc boy is brand new to us. . Rusty , like most border collies, loves people but is shy when he first meets them.   He is a play ball all day kind of boy.  If he can find a tennis ball, he'll put it in your hands or in your lap to encourage you to throw it so he can bring it right back to you.

He is gentle but unnerved by small kids so a home with older children or no children is important.

Rusty is good with other dogs but unknown how he is with cats.

Rusty is neutered, up to date on shots and on heartworm prevention. He is housebroken and well behaved inside but is hesitant to enter a room where a ceiling fan is running.  We expect he'll outgrow this in time.

 If you are interested in Rusty, please complete an online application at www.bordercollierescuewesttn.org or email us with questions at contact@bordercollierescuewesttn.org.

As with all of our dogs, we will require a fully fenced yard and excellent vet references.

Rusty's adoption fee is $300.  He is located in the Memphis area.
